Hey Friend,
Enrollment for all our courses is now open! üëèIn case you're curious, we offer
five unique courses specifically designed for different creative needs, and we
update them all the time to keep you up to date on the best possible techniques.
Our AI Filmmaking
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jq9theae5hwet54vpgf131yn/01jq9theae5hwet54vpp49tj0y]
course will teach you how to use all the tools for creating an original short
film. Advanced AI Filmmaking
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jq9theae5hwet54vpgf131yn/01jq9theae5hwet54vprq16w19]
, our newest course, is perfect for anyone familiar with the tools who is ready
to take their workflow to the next level. 
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jq9theae5hwet54vpgf131yn/01jq9theae5hwet54vpvnejbx2]
AI Advertising
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jq9theae5hwet54vpgf131yn/01jq9theae5hwet54vpwz9x6kq] 
 is
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jq9theae5hwet54vpgf131yn/01jq9theae5hwet54vpxp6cgdz]
a fantastic course for anyone who wants to elevate their marketing portfolio. AI
Documentary
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jq9theae5hwet54vpgf131yn/01jq9theae5hwet54vpya9hx46] 
will teach you how to bring unscripted narratives to life. AI Animation
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jq9theae5hwet54vpgf131yn/01jq9theae5hwet54vpz3ev92q]
, taught in partnership with our friends at Storybook Studios, will show you how
to make your very own original animated story.You can also check out our Course
Bundle
[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jq9theae5hwet54vpgf131yn/01jq9theae5hwet54vq2k86hh0] 
option to save on any 3 courses of your choice.Image item

[https://uqj77c.ff12.fdske.com/e/c/01jq9theae5hwet54vpgf131yn/01jq9theae5hwet54vq4a2wrsa]

stories to life. Our global community of students are always blowing our minds
with their creativity. We'd love for you to join us!If you have any questions at

column7: Your inbox deserves a deep breath
column9:
----------
Welcome to _The Daily Wisdom, _the email designed to help you live better every day_. _If you were forwarded this message, you can sign up to receive my free email [here](https://news.jayshetty.me/?utm_source=news.jayshetty.me&utm_medium=newsletter&utm_campaign=fresh-look-same-purpose&last_resource_guid=Post%3A4adba504-528c-49a4-98a8-d39ab3060dba&jwt_token=eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9.eyJzdWJzY3JpYmVyX2lkIjoiZjdjNzNmM2YtZjc3Zi00ZDhlLWFiYzctYWU0MjEzOTMwNTVkIiwicHVibGljYXRpb25faWQiOiI0MDUwODUwMi1kM2E0LTQ3ZGEtOTgxYS00NDAxMzEyYWQwZGUiLCJhY2Nlc3NfdHlwZSI6InJlYWQtb25seSIsImV4cCI6MTc2MTkzOTQ1MSwiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcHAuYmVlaGlpdi5jb20iLCJpYXQiOjE3NjE3NjY2NTF9.fpEW02IXWjBphCNx9yZe6sNAzlznSe7gnWomsQcIn_c).


--------------------
View image: (https://media.beehiiv.com/cdn-cgi/image/fit=scale-down,format=auto,onerror=redirect,quality=80/uploads/asset/file/a3abd8b6-7542-405d-ae53-f24dd2b81e29/DW-Newsletter-Quote__1_.png?t=1761887739)
Caption: 


--------------------
# Q: How can I make my inbox less stressful?

Today I want to talk about something that may seem a little silly ‚Äî _email_. 

Yep, that‚Äôs right. I‚Äôm writing you an email about email. Bear with me. It‚Äôs a big day around here! 

When I started out, my goal was simple: _make wisdom go viral. _For the past three years, I‚Äôve tried to do that through this newsletter, _Weekly Wisdom_. But lately‚Ä¶with everything going on in the world, once a week hasn‚Äôt felt like enough. 

So, starting today, _Weekly Wisdom _is now**_ _**_The Daily Wisdom_ ‚Äì the same newsletter 800,000 of you already subscribe to and share, now dropping in your inbox every weekday. 

You might be thinking, but why Jay? With so much noise in the world, would we add more, not less? But here‚Äôs the thing: 

[Ninety-nine percent of us check our inbox every single day, some of us twenty times or more](https://porchgroupmedia.com/blog/100-compelling-email-statistics-to-inform-your-strategy-in-2023/). And yet, most of the time, we leave feeling worse than when we arrived. We‚Äôre inundated with obligations and other people‚Äôs needs: messages waiting for answers, reminders, requests‚Ä¶notifications that quietly tug at our peace. 

The inbox has become a place of stress. 

But it wasn‚Äôt always this way. I remember when my inbox felt like a space for meaningful connection. Real correspondence with real people. 

Somewhere along the way, that shifted. The noise grew louder. Every ‚Äújust following up‚Äù became another layer of static in an already chaotic world ‚Äî one that demands we make decisions before we‚Äôve even had a chance to think. 

We‚Äôre pushed into action before we‚Äôre calm, clear, or ready. 

The thing is, across centuries and traditions, in all the work I‚Äôve studied from ancient philosophy to modern science, wisdom has actually followed the opposite rhythm:_ calm first, clarity second, action third. _

Your spiritual teacher and your medical doctor would both agree. 

It‚Äôs a simple code for living that helps us make better decisions from a place of calm, not chaos. When practised regularly, it allows us to move through our lives with more courage and confidence. No matter what questions arise ‚Äî from the small ones that shape your day, like _‚ÄúShould I speak up?‚Äù_ and _‚ÄúIs this worth my time?‚Äù _ to the big ones that shape your life like ‚ÄúWhat truly matters?‚Äù and _‚ÄúAm I on the right path?‚Äù ‚Äî _we always know what to do.

So when I thought about how I could help quiet the noise of the world, I realized I had two choices: stop sharing altogether or share more. And if I was going to share more, it had to serve a purpose: not to be yet another obligation, but to help restore the optimal rhythm of your mind. 

So, that‚Äôs what _The Daily Wisdom_ is here to deliver: a short message every weekday that offers one calming thought, one clear dose of wisdom, and one purposeful action to help you find that rhythm again, building your confidence one email at a time.

So yes, starting today, I _am_ filling your inbox more often. **If noise is daily, why should wisdom be anything less?¬†**

And if it resonates, I hope you‚Äôll share it with others in your life to help bring real connection and true correspondence back into the places we‚Äôve lost it most. 

Starting with your inbox.

Saturday‚Äôs episode of the podcast was the first in a mini-series featuring my wife, Radhi. We dove into a topic that I‚Äôm certain many of you have been faced with time and again: the decision to have children. Having children is one of the biggest decisions you can make in your life, and yet so many of us don‚Äôt stop to really think about the impact it will have on us and our relationships. In this loving conversation, we talk about the financial, emotional, and biological realities of starting a family in the modern age.

Caption: 



--------------------
# Today‚Äôs Wiser Choice

Those of you who know my work well know I‚Äôm a _humongous_ proponent of a morning ritual, especially one that keeps you _off your phone_. But, we need to accept the fact that some of the time we‚Äôre going to have to open our inboxes even when we don‚Äôt want to. So let‚Äôs do what we can to make it a more peaceful experience.

**Try This**: I want you to open up your email right now and just observe how you feel. Does it feel overwhelming? Disorganized? Or does it give you energy? Take out a piece of paper or note on your device and write down every little thing you observe. Like,

‚Äú_I sure get a lot of work emails that make me feel behind_.‚Äù

Or

‚Äú_There are so many newsletters here, but nothing that makes me feel better_.‚Äù

This exercise is not to make you feel bad ‚Äì it‚Äôs to give you awareness. Once you know how you feel, you can start taking steps to make yourself feel even _better_. Just like with your life, there‚Äôs no one-size-fits-all solution. The answer is whatever works best for _you_. So that when you inevitably open up your email at 8 am, it can be a peaceful experience instead of a stressful one.

column7: üëâ 3 Prompts To Help You Figure Out Your Goals
column9:
Hey friends,

Hope you‚Äôve had a good week - we had a couple of in-person events
in London last week and I find these sorts of gatherings so
valuable for my creativity and productivity. There‚Äôs something
about actually meeting people in-person, giving keynotes and
ultimately teaching that I find just so energising and fun.

Anyway, a few weeks ago we talked about the GPS framework that I
use for making consistent progress towards my goals, and today, I
thought I‚Äôd lean into the goal part of this a lot more and it was
actually one of the key questions that came up during the last
event we held in Hong Kong.

(Btw, if you‚Äôre interested in coming to one of these in the
future then make sure to keep an eye on my Instagram (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/wvugd3nzo9bghkwo3xea7hn6z5zxxi8h4lw6v/dphehmueq434d7il/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaW5zdGFncmFtLmNvbS9hbGlhYmRhYWwvP2hsPWVu
) stories as I‚Äôll post details about the next one there when I‚Äôm
back from the UK).

With this whole GPS thing, in order to have a good plan and a
good system, you need to have a clear goal - usually, a very
vague goal leads to very vague plans, very vague systems, and
then all sorts of problems.

And from what I‚Äôve seen from my friends, audience members and
customers is that most people are trying to juggle too many
things at once - they want to be a Hyrox athlete, be a
professional badminton player, make money from streaming,
whatever the thing is.

But the more you‚Äôre going all over the place and in all sorts of
directions, the harder it is to get anywhere and actually make
progress. When you get really clear on what exactly it is that
you want, then you can prioritise, manage your time, and put
plans and systems in place to help you achieve your goal.

I‚Äôve actually been working with business coaches for the last
five years, and I‚Äôm mostly focussed on the goal bit of the GPS
framework with my current business coach because clarity on that
single piece is so important.

Obviously, you don‚Äôt have to hire a business coach for thousands
of dollars to talk about your goals, and there are loads of
different (and free!) ways to figure out what you want to achieve
- I‚Äôve got a tonne of goal-related content on my YouTube channel
(in fact, the most viral video from the past year (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/wvugd3nzo9bghkwo3xea7hn6z5zxxi8h4lw6v/owhkhwuw4kzkxwiq/aHR0cHM6Ly95b3V0dS5iZS9XT05SUzdCTGg0Zz9zaT1VV1VFaDd5T29pZ2ZZbXpQ
) was about goals).

But you need to do it somehow, so I thought I‚Äôd share three
prompts in this email that you can use to help you do this.

One of my favourite questions is ‚Äúif you won the lottery
tomorrow, what would you change about your life?‚Äù because that
gives you some sense of what you‚Äôd do if financial constraints
were completely removed from the picture.

Another way to figure out your goal is by asking yourself
something that was inspired by Tim Urban: ‚ÄúWhat would I like my
ideal Tuesday to look like?‚Äù Assuming you‚Äôre doing some sort of
work (because let‚Äôs be honest, travel gets boring after a while
and not working also gets boring after a while), what would you
actually like to be doing on a normal Tuesday? What time would
you wake up? What would your morning routine look like? What
would you be doing for work? Try and zoom in and get really
granular with it.

A third approach is through building a vision board - imagine
your life three years in the future and think about what would be
really cool for you to accomplish in terms of health, work, and
relationships. You can then search for pictures that visualise
certain aspects of this dream life and organise them using Canva,
Figma, PowerPoint or something like that. My vision board is my
desktop wallpaper, so I‚Äôm reminded of what I‚Äôm working towards
every single day.

In terms of work, my goal is to have a nice lifestyle business
that does ¬£2 million a year in profit, where I can make videos on
my own terms sharing stuff that I think is cool, host in-person
events, and build apps like Voicepal.

Every now and then I‚Äôll attend something in the US and walk away
from it thinking ‚Äúman, I want to make more money.‚Äù But whenever
this happens, I get home and reflect, I look at my vision board
and think: ‚ÄúDo I want a ¬£50 million a year business?‚Äù because if
I do, I need to be doing very different things than for a ¬£2
million a year business. And I usually fire off a couple of
messages to my General Manager, Angus, telling him about some new
idea that could take us there but then after a few days (to be
honest, it‚Äôs now down to hours), I‚Äôve usually thought about it a
bit more and realised that chasing those numbers isn‚Äôt something
that aligns with the business that I want to build.

Anyway, that‚Äôs enough about my own work goals for now - if you‚Äôre
struggling to figure out what exactly it is that you want to
achieve, definitely have a think about those questions. I‚Äôd also
love to hear some of your answers, so feel free to hit reply and
share them with me.

And if you want to take this vision-setting piece further, it‚Äôs
wrapped up into the entire first half of LifeOS so if you‚Äôre keen
to really get clarity on your goals and path forward, you can
check it out here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/wvugd3nzo9bghkwo3xea7hn6z5zxxi8h4lw6v/z2hgh7ueo4g45psz/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWdvYWxzXzE4JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1wcm9kdWN0aXZlbm90ZXM=
).

Otherwise, that‚Äôs all for this week - speak soon üôè

Ali xx

# _**Welcome!**_

I hope you are well.

Here, you‚Äôll get to know 10 helpful tools you don‚Äôt know exist with the following information about every tool:

----------
1. **Potpie AI** 

  1. Description: Build custom agents using simple prompts that are expert on your codebase to perform engineering tasks for you. 

2. Category: AI agents 

3. Do they provide a free trial: Yes 

4. Website: [https://potpie.ai/](https://potpie.ai/) 

5. Core features: context-driven agents, easy chat, and coachable agents. 

6. ROI: Time saved for dev teams 

7. Tutorials: [Link](https://www.youtube.com/@PotpieAI/videos) 


2. **Zapier Agents** 

  1. Description: Create your custom AI agent in minutes. Equip your agents with live business data and have them do work across 7,000+ apps. 

2. Category: AI agents 

3. Do they provide a free trial: Yes 

4. Core features: Connect across 7000+ workspace apps, use templates, and try some agents they‚Äôve already created 

5. ROI: Time saved in manual work 

6. Website: [https://zapier.com/agents](https://zapier.com/agents) 

7. Tutorials: [Link](https://www.youtube.com/@Zapier/videos) 


3. **Claude Code and Claude 3.7 Sonnet** 

  1. Description: It's a hybrid reasoning model, producing near-instant responses or extended, step-by-step thinking. 

2. Category: LLM 

3. Do they provide a free trial: Yes 

4. Website: [https://claude.ai/](https://claude.ai/) 

5. Core features: dual thinking modes, excels in coding, supports long outputs (128K tokens), while Claude Code provides CLI-based agentic coding assistance for seamless development integration. 

6. ROI: Time saved in brainstorming, content generation, and coding 

7. Tutorials: [Link](https://youtu.be/x2WtHZciC74?si=RGedjiyKHMa5J8XT) 


4. **TestAI** 

  1. Description: 1,000+ automated tests for AI agents in one click 

2. Category: AI agents 

3. Do they provide a free trial: No 

4. Website: [https://www.nbulatest.ai/](https://www.nbulatest.ai/) 

5. Core features: fast setup, easy testing, real-time performance insights, and scenario testing. 

6. ROI: Time saved in testing 

7. Tutorials: Not available 


5. **Webflow‚Äôs AI Site Builder** 

  1. Description: Build your dream website in minutes with AI.

4. Website: [https://webflow.com/ai-site-builder](https://webflow.com/ai-site-builder) 

5. Core features: website creation, multiple page creation, copywriting, theme creation, complete website design, and more.

  1. Description: a multi-agent AI research assistant that conducts systematic literature reviews like a researcher. It enhances search queries, analyzes vast datasets, and delivers the most relevant paper, 10X better than Open AI Deep Research for academic research.

column7: You can ditch your email marketing tool (if you want)
column9:
https://podia37110.lt.acemlnb.com/Prod/link-tracker?redirectUrl=aHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZwb2RpYS5jb20=&sig=88j9gnKupCCVyKnLKQQYpdJwWUtLRnmMemVtYzKh5R43&iat=1717699830&a=%7C%7C610920696%7C%7C&account=podia37110%2Eactivehosted%2Ecom&email=t9eeHF%2BfdrBrirR6Ihx7Faxkxro2mocwHGy32ZKxepC5cBrUFCDktw%3D%3D%3APFk%2BVmYWzTMrlGxwLzIckHmPw%2BvaoSfZ&s=af0c5888650599f2bb8a20a9d248faf8&i=812A879A21A29664 

Hi Cassie,

Something that surprises most people starting a business (were you surprised? I know I was) is that you have to use 

**so. many. tools.¬†**

There's a tool for everything! And they're all different. And you have to learn how to use each one from scratch. And you have to figure out how to get them to connect to each other. And fewer of them are free than you would like.¬†

**Podia Email**  was designed to let you get rid of your email marketing tool. Instead of having to figure out how to integrate two things that don't ever seem to work together, it puts the most important email features in one place. Features like:

* 

**Beautifully designed emails with beautiful templates**. Your emails need to look great, so Podia Email uses an easy design system and lets you start from a professionally-designed template.¬†

* 

**Segmentation (including stuff you can't get anywhere else).** You want to send the right emails to the right people - and Podia Email actually does that better than most platforms, because it includes info like customer sales that you can't get in isolated, standalone email tools.

* 

**Automated emails.** Welcome emails and other automated campaigns help you get in front of your audience right after they sign up (when they're most likely to keep consuming your work).

Podia Email is free for the first 100 subscribers, then starts at $7 per month (a price that, last I checked, beats everything else on the market). Feel free to start **playing around with the platform yourself** , or check out some **examples of what other people like you have built with Podia Email** .

When you're ready, you can upgrade your Podia Email plan in your account - and hopefully cut out another tool (and headache) that comes with running an online business.

Best,

Spencer, founder and CEO of Podia

P.S. If you do want to use another email tool, that's ok too - Podia integrates with 8 of the most popular ones. **More info here** !

column7: The Step-by-Step Guide to Starting a Podcast
column9:
(
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/75uo4omv5pf2um07xdb5tqkk8r66in/n2hohvh3xwx7gdc6/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnV6enNwcm91dC5jb20=
)

Starting a podcast is hard work.

You start with an idea, but there are tons of small things you
have to learn along the way. Our mission at Buzzsprout is to make
podcasting easier, so that you can get your message out to the
world.

That's why we created a step-by-step guide to starting a podcast
(
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/75uo4omv5pf2um07xdb5tqkk8r66in/48hvhehrpzpxqzsx/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnV6enNwcm91dC5jb20vYmxvZy9ob3ctdG8tc3RhcnQtYS1wb2RjYXN0
). We first wrote the guide in 2014, but we've updated it dozens
of times since then. It's been read over 3 million times and has
helped launch at least 300,000 podcasts.

The guide covers everything you need to start podcasting,
including:

* How to develop your podcast concept
* What recording equipment to buy
* How to record your first episode
* How to edit and export your episode
* How to upload your episode to Buzzsprout, and
* How to get listed in Apple Podcasts, Spotify, and Google

Hey Candace,

It‚Äôs Thursday, and with Friday on the horizon, you might be
feeling the pressure to get those last few tasks ticked off your
to-do list.

Maybe more tasks have crept onto your workload since the start of
the week, and now you‚Äôre facing the dreaded Thursday scramble.

One of the best ways to avoid feeling overwhelmed is to
consolidate and prioritise. Instead of trying to tackle
everything at once, focus on just a few key tasks that will move
the needle the most.

But here‚Äôs the tricky bit: knowing which tasks are the most
important to prioritise.

When I was writing Feel-Good Productivity (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh226gedbrh43mgnnnf7/58hvh8umex5xl4b7/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmVlbGdvb2Rwcm9kdWN0aXZpdHkuY29tLw==
), I came across a concept that completely changed how I approach
my daily to-do list: the Three Daily Quests.

It‚Äôs a simple but powerful method that helps me stay aligned with
my long-term goals while making each day feel manageable.

Here‚Äôs how it works:

Each morning, I choose three key actions that will move me a
little closer to where I want to be in a year‚Äôs time. I divide
these actions into three categories: Health, Relationships, and
Work.

For example, my Three Daily Quests for today might look like
this:

ü§∏ Health: Go to the gym from 3:30-4:30 PM üßë‚Äçüíª Work: Make progress
on writing my newsletter LifeNotes (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh226gedbrh43mgnnnf7/25h2h9u25979nxs8/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXIv
) ‚Äãüßë‚Äçü§ù‚Äçüßë Relationships: Call my grandma, Nani

But this method isn‚Äôt just for fitness enthusiasts, writers, or
those who love calling their grandma like I do.

If you‚Äôre someone who‚Äôs passionate about a side hustle while
working a full-time job, your three quests could look like:

ü§∏ Health: Do a 30-minute HIIT workout after work to recharge üßë‚Äçüíª
Work: Dedicate an hour in the evening to developing your side
hustle ‚Äãüßë‚Äçü§ù‚Äçüßë Relationships: Grab lunch with your friend Tony

Or if you‚Äôre a working parent, juggling the demands of your job,
your health, and your family life, your quests might include:

ü§∏ Health: Do a quick 15-minute home workout before the kids wake
up üßë‚Äçüíª Work: Finish drafting that important email before
lunchtime ‚Äãüßë‚Äçü§ù‚Äçüßë Relationships: Read a bedtime story to your kids

The idea is simple: when we break down our big goals into
smaller, actionable steps, they become a lot less intimidating
and a lot more achievable.

Instead of scrambling to get everything done and feeling guilty
if you don‚Äôt, the 3 Daily Quests help you focus on what really
matters by asking, ‚ÄúWhat are the 3 core things I can do to get
80% of the way there?‚Äù

This approach is backed by research, too. In one famous study (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh226gedbrh43mgnnnf7/g3hnhwu3v9e9g7s3/aHR0cHM6Ly9wc3ljbmV0LmFwYS5vcmcvcmVjb3JkLzE5ODItMDc1MjctMDAx
), psychologists found that kids who focused on short-term
targets, like completing a few pages of math problems each day,
performed twice as well as those who focused on long-term goals.
Not only did they solve more problems, but they also felt more
confident in their abilities.

Now, what if the tasks you need to tackle are really boring?

Here‚Äôs a trick to help you hack your mindset: instead of thinking
about your most important things to do as tasks, think of them as
quests.

Tasks can feel like obligations, but quests make you feel like
you‚Äôre on an exciting journey.

For example, imagine you have to create and send five invoices.
One way to turn this task into something fun might be to do it
from your favourite cafeteria while you sip on a chai latte and
listen to Harry Potter music. Or maybe add a challenge and see if
you can complete each invoice and send it in less than five
minutes.

Framing your work as a quest can bring positive emotions and a
feel-good vibe to what you have to do. It‚Äôs a simple shift in
perspective that can make even the dullest tasks feel a bit more
adventurous.

So, what are the three quests you‚Äôll embark on today that will
move you closer to achieving your goals?

-----------------------------------
üì¢ Challenge: The Three Daily Quests
-----------------------------------

Ready to avoid the Thursday scramble? Here‚Äôs your challenge:

* Grab a sticky note or notebook.
* Write down three tasks for today that will generate 80% of your
results. These should cover Health, Relationships, and Work.
Think about what will make the biggest impact with the least
effort.
* Write down an affirmation to help you flip the confidence
switch and stay motivated throughout the day. Ask yourself, ‚ÄúWhat
would it look like if I were really confident at this?‚Äù. Then,
jot down a phrase like, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm approaching this task with
confidence and skill,‚Äù or ‚ÄúI‚Äôm going to act as if I‚Äôve got this,
even if I‚Äôm unsure.‚Äù

Share your list and affirmation with me by hitting reply to keep
yourself accountable.

And remember to keep your list somewhere you can see it
throughout the day as a reminder of what‚Äôs important

By focusing on just three key quests, you‚Äôll finish the day
feeling accomplished and ready to tackle whatever Friday throws
your way. Tomorrow, we‚Äôll be wrapping up the week with tips on
how to reflect on your progress and prepare for the next one.

Before I leave you until tomorrow: This challenge is just a small
example of the productivity systems that I‚Äôve built into
Productivity Lab to help you take your productivity to the next
level.

So, if you‚Äôve been enjoying things so far this week then you may
also be interested in joining Productivity Lab which re-opens its
doors on Monday (17th February). But I‚Äôll tell you more about
that then üòú

Ali xx

‚Äã

References:

* Bandura, A., & Schunk, D.H. (1981). Cultivating competence,
self-efficacy, and intrinsic interest through proximal
self-motivation. Journal of Personality and Social Psychology,
41(3):586‚Äì598.

column7: Still call yourself a freelance writer?
column9:
Hey !

What‚Äôs the best way to start landing high-paying writing
opportunities (even if you‚Äôve never ghostwritten for anyone
before)?

Call yourself a Premium Ghostwriter.

It‚Äôs literally that simple.

Why? Because words matter.

So, if you‚Äôre about to start your ghostwriting side hustle (or
you‚Äôre in the early stages), then stop and make this one crucial
change before you continue.

Here‚Äôs why:

*****************************************************************
What you call yourself is THE position you hold in your customers
mind (and their wallet).
*****************************************************************

When you hear the term ‚ÄúFreelance Writer,‚Äù what do you think of?

It‚Äôs probably something like: an underpaid, over-caffeinated,
jack-of-all-trades writer, who spends hours on Upwork competing
for gigs by trying to undercut the competition. Is that what you
want? Probably not.

So, stop calling yourself a Freelance Writer.

And start calling yourself a Premium Ghostwriter.

‚Äã
Here are 3 more reasons why calling yourself a ‚ÄúPremium
Ghostwriter‚Äù is the best way to differentiate yourself as a
writer on the internet:

*****************************************************************
Reason #1: Ghostwriting implies that you are NOT an average
freelance writer.
*****************************************************************

Millions of people call themselves ‚Äúfreelance writers.‚Äù

When you call yourself the same exact thing, you are making it
HARDER for yourself to stand out. Simply by calling yourself
something other than a ‚Äúfreelance writer,‚Äù you immediately remove
yourself from the pack and stand out. Yes, that‚Äôs literally how
it works.

Calling yourself a ‚ÄúPremium Ghostwriter‚Äù is the fastest way to
start separating yourself from the competition.

*****************************************************************
Reason #2: Ghostwriting means you‚Äôre hired by a business leader
(not a business).
*****************************************************************

As a ghostwriter, you work directly with business leaders and so
you unlock higher levels of opportunity.

Freelance writers are typically hired by content marketing teams
to churn out branded content:

* eBooks
* Blog posts
* Landing pages

Since these are highly commoditized assets, and there are
millions of freelance writers, many of these writers are treated
like virtual assistants (and paid accordingly). It‚Äôs a race to
the bottom. Ghostwriting allows you to work directly with an
industry leader in a highly specialized capacity.

And once you become friends with a business leader, they will
inevitably send more specialized ($$$) work your way.

*****************************************************************
Reason #3: Ghostwriting positions you as a business consultant
(who just happens to be an all-star writer).
*****************************************************************

When you ghostwrite, you get paid to do more than just write‚Äîyou
get paid to give business advice.

* You help your clients craft compelling offers & narratives.
* You help them spot bottlenecks in their marketing funnels.
* You help them implement the best strategies to scale their
message online.

As a result clients value ‚Äúghostwriting‚Äù much more highly than
freelance writing. They see you as ‚Äúpremium,‚Äù which gives you
much more pricing power.

As a ghostwriter, you set the agenda and make recommendations to
the client (rather than taking orders like any other
‚Äúfreelancer‚Äù).

‚Äã

*****************************************************************
This is how ghostwriters command top-tier opportunities and
premium pricing.
*****************************************************************

They have clarity over what they‚Äôre offering.

They don‚Äôt ‚Äúcompete‚Äù over commoditized jobs.

And they‚Äôre different‚Äîjust by calling themselves a Premium
Ghostwriter!

That‚Äôs it!

Dickie & Cole

Co-Founders, Premium Ghostwriting Academy

PS... Once you've changed your positioning, here're 4 other
tactics you could implement to build trust & command even higher
prices as a ghostwriter. (

column8: üåü Make 2025 Your Most Productive Year Yet
column10:
Hey Candace,

At the end of 1999, as the world counted down to the new
millennium, there was a unique mix of excitement and uncertainty.
The Y2K bug was on everyone‚Äôs mind, with fears that computers
would fail, systems would collapse, and chaos might ensue.

But as midnight struck on December 31st, nothing catastrophic
happened.

Instead, people around the world celebrated the dawn of a new
era. It was a moment of reflection and renewal ‚Äî a chance to
leave the past behind and look forward to the possibilities of a
new century.

Moments like these, whether it‚Äôs the turn of a century or the end
of a year, are what psychologists call "temporal landmarks."
These are points in time that allow us to step back, evaluate our
progress, and think about where we want to go next.

What‚Äôs fascinating is how these moments create what researchers
call the "fresh start effect."

The Power of Reflection

Reflection isn‚Äôt just a feel-good exercise. It‚Äôs one of the most
powerful tools we have for growth.

In a study published in Harvard Business Review, researchers
found that people who reflect regularly on their work perform
significantly better than those who don‚Äôt. This is because
reflection allows us to identify patterns, understand what‚Äôs
working (and what isn‚Äôt), and make deliberate adjustments.

It also gives us a chance to celebrate progress.

Too often, we focus on what we didn‚Äôt achieve or what went wrong,
overlooking the small wins that got us closer to where we want to
be. But those small wins matter.

In fact, Teresa Amabile‚Äôs research on motivation found that
recognising incremental progress is one of the most effective
ways to sustain long-term momentum.

So, as we close out 2024, take a moment to look back. What went
well? What surprised you? And what lessons will you carry forward
into 2025?

Make 2025 Your Most Productive Year Yet

But reflection is only half the equation. The real magic happens
when we take those lessons and turn them into a plan of action.

That‚Äôs exactly why I‚Äôm hosting Productivity Spark 2025, a live,
interactive summit on 4-5 January designed to help you reflect on
the year that‚Äôs passed and create a roadmap for the year ahead.

This isn‚Äôt just about setting goals or chasing the idea of being
"productive." It‚Äôs about creating a system that aligns with what
truly matters to you, so you can approach 2025 with clarity,
confidence, and consistency.

Through practical workshops, hands-on exercises, and actionable
sessions with myself and other guest speakers, we‚Äôll work
together to:

* Reflect deeply on the wins, challenges, and lessons of 2024.
* Identify the goals that matter most to you in 2025.
* Build a step-by-step plan to make those goals a reality.

So, if you want to start 2025 with clarity, focus, and a system
for taking consistent action, this is the event for you and you
can register your interest by clicking the link below

column7: MIDS Data for Good Fellowship‚ÄîLearn More
column9:
<https://ischoolonline.berkeley.edu/data-science/>
 
Dear Prospective Student,

As part of the I School's continued commitment to shape the future of data science by promoting its efforts to serve the public good, the I School offers the Jack Larson Data for Good Fellowship <https://ischoolonline.berkeley.edu/admissions/tuition-financial-aid/fellowships/>. This fellowship is designed to support MIDS students in their pursuit of a career that will allow them to improve human life and benefit society as a whole.

One $8,500 fellowship will be awarded to one MIDS student per cohort over the next two years. Eligible applicants will have demonstrated how they intend to use the skills they will acquire in the MIDS program to drive social change.

GO TO YOUR APPLICATION >>
<https://apply.datascience.berkeley.edu/signup>

NO GRE/GMAT REQUIRED
 
The priority application deadline for the September 2025 cohort is April 23. To learn more about the fellowship, visit the datascience@berkeley website <https://ischoolonline.berkeley.edu/admissions/tuition-financial-aid/fellowships/>. To request an application for the Jack Larson Data for Good Fellowship, please contact your Admissions Counselor directly at 855-678-6437 or slee2@datascience.berkeley.edu.
 
Sincerely,
 
datascience@berkeley Admissions
UC Berkeley School of Information
ischoolonline.berkeley.edu
855-678-6437

AI Snacks p*

Bite-sized AI news, fresh daily





Hey Snackers,
B
Google's parent company Alphabet just crossed into the $3 trillion market cap club, riding a wave of AI optimism and a favorable
antitrust ruling that let them keep Chrome and Android in the family. The milestone puts them alongside Apple, Microsoft, and
Nvidia in tech's most exclusive wealth bracket.
B
Meanwhile, OpenAI's board chair Bret Taylor is out here admitting we're in an AI bubblebbut hey, at least he's comparing it to the
dotbcom era, when the wreckage eventually birthed Amazon and Google. So there's that.
B
Speaking of reality checks, senior developers are discovering that AI coding assistants have turned them into glorified "AI
babysitters"bspending more time fixing buggy, insecure code than if they'd just written it themselves. One dev compared it to
asking a "smart sixbyearbold" to pour coffee for the family. Sure, it might work, but you'll probably end up mopping the floor.

 * p, ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, Grok, Llama, Perplexity, DeepSeek

 * p( Midjourney, Ideogram, Leonardo, Stable Diffusion, DALLB7E 3, Flux, Nano Banana, GPT-Image

 * p, Veo 3, Luma, Kling, Pika, HeyGen, RunwayML, Hailuo (Minimax)

 * p5 ElevenLabs, Lyria, Hedra, CassetteAI

 * p Works seamlessly on web, iOS, and Android

 * p	 Join millions who have switched to Galaxy.ai [https://galaxy.ai]




EMPIRE STATE OF MIND
[https://techcrunch.com/2025/09/14/karen-hao-on-the-empire-of-ai-agi-evangelists-and-the-cost-of-belief/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]


OpenAI accused of building an "Empire of AI" that rivals nationbstates

Journalist Karen Hao's new book "Empire of AI" paints OpenAI as more powerful than most countries, driven by an almost religious
belief in Artificial General Intelligence that justifies any means to achieve it.
B
The book argues that the race for AGI has prioritized speed over safety, with the entire industry just throwing more data and
computing power at the same old methods instead of exploring safer, more innovative approaches.
B
 * Hao questions whether OpenAI's mission to "benefit all humanity" holds up when their quest comes with massive environmental,
   social, and ethical costs

 * The critique comes as OpenAI continues its relentless expansion, backed by Microsoft's billions and a valuation approaching
   $150b/billion

 * It's essentially the tech equivalent of "move fast and break things," except this time the "things" might include society as we
   know it

B
THE TAKEAWAY
The AI industry is having its "are we the baddies?" moment. When your own leadership admits you're in a bubble AND journalists are
comparing you to an empire, maybe it's time to pump the brakes. But with billions on the line and AGI as the prize, that's about
as likely as ChatGPT writing bugbfree code on the first try.




GOOGLE'S CONTENT HEIST
[https://www.reuters.com/business/alphabet-hits-3-trillion-market-capitalization-first-time-2025-09-15/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]


Rolling Stone owner sues Google over AI summaries that steal traffic

B
Penske Media Corporation, which owns Rolling Stone, Variety, and other major publications, is suing Google for using their content
to generate AI summaries that keep users from clicking through to actual articles.
B
The lawsuit claims Google's AI Overviews feature breaks the "fundamental bargain" of the internet:
 * Publishers have always given search engines access to their content in exchange for traffic

 * Now Google is using that same content to create AI summaries that answer questions directly in search results

 * This means fewer clicks, less ad revenue, and fewer subscriptions for publishers

 * PMC argues this is straightbup content theft dressed up as innovation

B
Google, for its part, maintains that AI Overviews actually increase clicks to publishers. Which is a bit like a burglar claiming
they're helping you declutter.
B
THE TAKEAWAY
This lawsuit could reshape the entire internet economy. If publishers win, Google might have to completely rethink how AI
summaries workbor start cutting some very large checks. If Google wins, we might be witnessing the slow death of the traditional
web publishing model. Either way, the lawyers are about to make bank.




NVIDIA's INSURANCE POLICY
[https://www.reuters.com/business/coreweave-nvidia-sign-63-billion-cloud-computing-capacity-order-2025-09-15/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]


CoreWeave locks in $6.3b/billion backstop from Nvidia in massive cloud deal

AI data center operator CoreWeave just signed a $6.3b/billion deal with Nvidia that essentially guarantees they'll never have
unsold capacitybNvidia will buy whatever their other customers don't.
B
This isn't just a business deal; it's a fullbon safety net:
 * CoreWeave provides access to Nvidia's coveted GPUs to companies like Microsoft and OpenAI

 * The deal ensures CoreWeave can keep expanding without worrying about demand

 * It shows just how desperate the market is for AI computing power

 * Nvidia basically just became CoreWeave's sugar daddy AND their biggest customer

B
The arrangement is like a restaurant owner promising to eat any food that doesn't sell. Except instead of leftover pasta, we're
talking about billions in cloud computing capacity.
B
THE TAKEAWAY
The AI gold rush has created some truly wild business models. Nvidia is so confident in AI demand that they're willing to bet
$6.3b/billion on backstopping a single customer. This either ends with everyone getting rich or the most expensive "I told you so"
in tech history.




THE BEST THING WE READ TODAY
[https://techcrunch.com/2025/09/14/vibe-coding-has-turned-senior-devs-into-ai-babysitters-but-they-say-its-worth-it/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]


Senior devs become "AI babysitters" in the age of "vibe coding"

Experienced programmers are discovering that AI coding assistants have fundamentally changed their jobband not necessarily for the
better. Instead of writing code, they're now fixing and factbchecking the buggy, insecure output from their AI "helpers."
B
This phenomenon, dubbed "vibe coding," involves using AI to quickly generate initial ideas that often require complete rewrites.
It's less "pair programming" and more "teaching your nephew to code while he's hopped up on Mountain Dew."

Hey friends,

I‚Äôve recently been re-reading the book Designing Your Life (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8um4n02d7uoh320q3zu2hd79mn66s7/3ohphdu7856nnetp/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL1VjQWFT
) by Bill Burnett and Dave Evans, which applies design thinking
to lifestyle design. In the book, they talk a lot about running
experiments because you don‚Äôt really know what you want until you
come up with a hypothesis about what you think you might want and
then run the smallest possible experiment to prove the theory.
Tim Ferriss also explores this concept in The 4-Hour Workweek (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8um4n02d7uoh320q3zu2hd79mn66s7/n2hohqu349wkk7c0/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL1UwbXplUGs=
), highlighting how small experiments can guide major life
decisions.

I applied this to my own life back in 2020. I‚Äôd just taken a
break from medicine and was planning to move to Australia, but
then the pandemic hit and the borders shut down. That was the
year I accidentally became a full-time YouTuber.

At that time, my dream life still included practising medicine
part-time, about 2-3 days a week, while spending the rest of the
week doing YouTube and business stuff. I‚Äôd seen first-hand that
the happiest doctors I knew seemed to be those who worked
part-time. This seemed reasonable. Doctors could continue
practicing medicine, which they love, while avoiding burnout.

But then I remembered all these experimental stuff and then
thought, why don‚Äôt I just test this instead of committing to a
medical training pathway and then then requesting for permission
to go down to three days a week, only to then find out that I
might not enjoy that?

I decided to take extra shifts at the hospital to model what
working three days a week in medicine would look like. I quickly
realised, ‚ÄúOh, this is actually not that fun.‚Äù

Every 20 minutes, I would start thinking, ‚ÄúI‚Äôd rather be at
WeWork making YouTube videos or working on the business or
playing table tennis with my team.‚Äù When I was working on YouTube
with the gang, I felt excited. But in the evenings before
upcoming shifts, I would dread going to work the next day, and
really not look forward to spending hours on the phone trying to
get hold of the neurosurgical registrar to refer a patient.

By running this experiment for just a few weeks, I saved myself a
copious amount of time‚Äîpotentially years‚Äîof chasing a path I
ultimately wouldn‚Äôt have enjoyed.

This leads us to the idea of minimum viable experiments.

These days, I get questions from students, people in their 20s,
even those in their 30s and above with some variant of: ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt
like my job. What should I do? What steps should I take?‚Äù

If we run with this experimentation idea, the next steps would be
to think of what you might enjoy, then run a minimum viable
experiment to test it out.

For example, if you think you might want to be a doctor but
you‚Äôre not entirely sure, a poor life choice would be to apply to
medical school, spend 6+ years in training, and then learn that
you don‚Äôt like it.

There are other lower-stakes way to test out the same hypothesis:

* Shadow a doctor for a weekend
* Do some medical work experience
* Speak to other doctors about their experience
* Chill at a hospital cafeteria, sit at a table with doctors, and
ask them questions

These tiny experiments that would test your hypotheses way
quicker and give you a lot more data points compared to applying
to a medical school.

So in case you‚Äôre thinking of trying something new, find the
minimum viable experiment that could test out your hypothesis.

I‚Äôd love to hear what you come up with. Hit reply and let me
know.

Have a great week!

Ali xx

- Zhenya Globazh, UX designer at Adobe, explores a close, early-stage collaboration between growth design and user research can do more than just polish features‚Äîit can uncover new user needs, solve real problems, and drive meaningful outcomes.

- By combining growth design‚Äôs data-driven experimentation with user research‚Äôs deep understanding of user behaviors, teams can quickly adapt while ensuring product changes remain intuitive and impactful.

- Integrating research and growth design isn‚Äôt just helpful, it's essential. When designers work closely with researchers, it creates a feedback loop that can refine ideas, test assumptions, and ultimately deliver better products and more user-centered experiences.

AI Prompting Is a Design Act (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/DVVxP3sxP_W2rj1n_349p8mW8fXtNV5C4pYfN4zFKM63l5QzW7Y8-PT6lZ3nmW8vW-QX7qSQDZW7rrtzN6WXlrbMCM7rDYHfHdVZHKFZ5X1GdGW1VlH7162P5JCW5lsjdj79V_WNW4J3zG-8scsN4W8Rkx_y22LD8nW6RC4wQ3YPyM4W96cl6y191VPyW1x-PSZ54N4RZW3LkBjg7RBr11W2ycdWJ5SC8f0W4ZGYVb958HQ_W50yVYg6PmdC9W92vw-78QWW_BW5KLlXl772cK9W4WLLhW6hh_8hW4nrDxB3gd28cW4NH1RF1tRTykW1yMRwB2VsL8QW5X58C15z4Sw0W28L8Xs9bKmD6W1c2KxM3RY98lW84h9tf8j0VcvTczFz8z6mgqf1S84Gz04 )

- UX designer Lyndon Cerejo argues that prompting AI should be viewed as a design act‚Äîakin to crafting a creative brief or designing a conversation‚Äîrather than simply issuing instructions.

- The article highlights three key lessons: treat AI like a smart but context-lacking intern; guide and verify its outputs rather than trusting blindly; and structure prompts thoughtfully to shape behavior and tone.

- ‚ÄúAs designers, we‚Äôre used to designing interactions for people. Prompting is us designing our own interactions with machines ‚Äî it uses the same mindset with a new medium.‚Äù

Case Study: Why Digital Celebrations Backfire  (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/DVVxP3sxP_W2rj1n_349p8mW8fXtNV5C4pYfN4zFKLx3l5QzW6N1vHY6lZ3kGW1yfr5X26xxH6W7YMDt-5XYFhjVb-dN11zWXsBW6Qm_Pt4h5pcVW7mZ-h82CLyrjW3MLbM53F92wBW20-rX32Jn-FGW6GhCh24NrLYNW9kdTV7603-BzN5HpBrz1KW4QW88Hsw73jcGQ-W3cb8yn7Qs90vW9gJbby6v-SZSW8Sg97k80Tc4lW7TMFKx3F86BlW9jw6jj7PfDYRW2SxLSt8yfnlgW17vCrp5-f8FvW2h1tHS36SCKCW8Lp1GY3bBqK9W9ctwK53fQ-l6VrQ15p6Gm5_Pf3cpcCR04 )

- UX consultant Peter Ramsey explores how designing impactful, emotionally resonant moments can elevate ‚Äúboring‚Äù experiences‚Äîusing banking app Chase as an example‚Äîby turning poorly executed celebrations into meaningful interactions.

- Ramsey argues that celebratory moments, such as congrats screens or digital confetti, should only be used when they align with genuine user goals‚Äîfor example, completing a meaningful action‚Äîrather than arbitrary milestones like account sign-ups.

- ‚ÄúThe risk of poorly-designed moments isn't just that they fail to make an impact. They can break the relationship between the user and the product‚Ä¶ the celebration simply exposes a contradiction between what the user wants to do, and what the company is forcing on them."
